## Factory Mode

When invoked with `/factory TICKET-{id}`:
- All human gates use auto-defaults
- Ticket readiness checked automatically (`/check-readiness`)
- Code standards validated locally -- **deployment handled by CI**
- PR gets `factory` label -> triggers CI workflows
- On halt: notify team, do not wait for user

### Pipeline

```
/draft-story (architect resolves questions)
    -> Ticket "Ready for Sprint"
    |
/factory TICKET-xxx
  |-- /check-readiness
  |-- Create worktree + branch
  |-- Scaffold + implement
  |-- /validate (code standards only)
  |-- Commit + PR (factory label) -> CI deploys -> reviewer tests -> merge -> deploy
```

## Common Development Commands

### Code Formatting & Linting

```bash
make lint              # Run ruff linter
make lint-fix          # Auto-fix linting issues
make format            # Format with ruff format
make format-check      # Check formatting without modifying (runs in CI)
make typecheck         # Run mypy strict type checking
make check             # Run all of the above in sequence
```

### Testing

```bash
make test              # Run full test suite (pytest)
make test-unit         # Unit tests only (fast, no DB or Redis)
make test-integration  # Integration tests (requires local Docker services)
make test-e2e          # End-to-end API tests against running server
make test-coverage     # Generate HTML coverage report (target: 85%)
make test-watch        # Re-run tests on file changes (pytest-watch)
```

### Database

```bash
make db-upgrade        # Run pending Alembic migrations
make db-downgrade      # Roll back last migration
make db-revision MSG="description"  # Generate new migration from model changes
make db-seed           # Seed local database with sample data
make db-reset          # Drop all tables, re-run migrations, re-seed
```

### Local Development

```bash
make dev               # Start FastAPI with hot-reload (port 8000)
make dev-full          # Start API + Celery worker + Celery beat via docker-compose
make docker-up         # Start PostgreSQL + Redis containers
make docker-down       # Stop and remove containers
```

### Deployment

```bash
make build             # Build Docker image for deployment
make deploy-dev        # Deploy to dev (triggers GitHub Actions workflow)
make deploy-staging    # Deploy to staging (requires passing CI)
# Production deploys require manual approval in GitHub Actions after staging verification
```

## Development Guidelines

### Coding Standards

- Follow PEP 8 and PEP 257; enforced by ruff with strict configuration
- Use type hints on all function signatures and return types; enforced by mypy in strict mode
- Use `snake_case` for variables, functions, and modules; `PascalCase` for classes and Pydantic models
- Maximum function length: 30 lines; extract private helpers for anything longer
- All public functions and classes must have Google-style docstrings
- Use `from __future__ import annotations` in every module for modern type syntax
- Prefer composition over inheritance; use Protocols (structural subtyping) over ABCs where possible
- All database queries must go through the repository layer (`src/repositories/`) -- never import SQLAlchemy models in route handlers
- Use dependency injection via FastAPI's `Depends()` for services, repositories, and auth
- Constants go in `src/core/constants.py`; never use magic numbers or strings inline

### Error Handling

- All API errors return structured JSON: `{ "error": { "code": "APPOINTMENT_CONFLICT", "message": "...", "details": {...} } }`
- Use custom exception classes in `src/core/exceptions.py` that map to HTTP status codes
- Register exception handlers in `src/core/exception_handlers.py` for consistent responses
- Log all exceptions with `structlog` including `request_id`, `user_id`, and `trace_id` context
- HIPAA-sensitive fields (patient names, SSN, DOB) must be redacted from all log output using the `SensitiveFieldFilter`
- Background tasks (Celery) must catch and log all exceptions; use dead-letter queues for failed tasks
- Never return raw Python exceptions or tracebacks in API responses

### Testing Strategy

- **Unit tests** (pytest): Required for all business logic in `src/services/` and `src/core/` -- minimum 85% line coverage
- **Integration tests**: Test API endpoints with a real test database (PostgreSQL in Docker); test Celery tasks with a real Redis broker
- **Contract tests**: Validate FHIR resource serialization against the HL7 FHIR R4 schema
- **E2E tests**: Full API flow tests covering appointment booking, insurance verification, and provider scheduling
- Use factories in `tests/factories/` (factory_boy) for test data -- never hardcode patient IDs, provider IDs, or dates
- External services (EHR APIs, insurance APIs) are mocked with `responses` library at the HTTP boundary
- All tests must be idempotent and isolated; use database transactions that roll back after each test
- CI runs the full suite on every push; PRs cannot merge if any test fails or coverage drops below 85%

## Code Organization

```
src/
  api/
    v1/
      routes/             # Route handlers grouped by domain
        appointments.py
        providers.py
        patients.py
        insurance.py
        auth.py
      dependencies.py     # Shared FastAPI dependencies for v1
    middleware/            # Request/response middleware (logging, CORS, rate limiting)
  core/
    config.py             # Settings via pydantic-settings (reads from env vars)
    constants.py          # Application-wide constants
    exceptions.py         # Custom exception classes
    exception_handlers.py # FastAPI exception handler registrations
    security.py           # JWT token handling, permission decorators
  models/                 # SQLAlchemy ORM models
    appointment.py
    provider.py
    patient.py
    insurance_plan.py
    clinical_note.py
  schemas/                # Pydantic v2 request/response schemas
    appointment.py
    provider.py
    patient.py
  repositories/           # Data access layer (one per model)
    base.py               # Generic CRUD repository
    appointment.py
    provider.py
    patient.py
  services/               # Business logic layer
    appointment.py        # Scheduling, conflict detection, reminders
    insurance.py          # Verification, eligibility checks
    fhir.py               # HL7 FHIR resource mapping and EHR sync
    notification.py       # Email, SMS, push notification dispatch
  tasks/                  # Celery async tasks
    reminders.py          # Appointment reminder scheduling
    sync.py               # EHR synchronization jobs
    reports.py            # Nightly report generation
  integrations/           # External service clients
    ehr/                  # EHR system adapters (Epic, Cerner)
    stripe.py             # Billing and payment processing
    twilio.py             # SMS delivery
    sendgrid.py           # Email delivery
alembic/
  versions/               # Migration scripts
  env.py                  # Alembic environment configuration
tests/
  unit/                   # Unit tests (mirrors src/ structure)
  integration/            # API and database integration tests
  e2e/                    # Full flow end-to-end tests
  factories/              # factory_boy model factories
  conftest.py             # Shared fixtures (db session, test client, auth tokens)
infra/
  terraform/              # Infrastructure as code
    modules/
      ecs/                # ECS Fargate service definitions
      rds/                # PostgreSQL RDS configuration
      elasticache/        # Redis cluster configuration
      alb/                # Application Load Balancer
    environments/
      dev/
      staging/
      prod/
  docker/
    Dockerfile            # Multi-stage production image
    docker-compose.yml    # Local development services
```

## Version Control

### Branching Strategy

- **`main`** -- primary integration branch; always deployable to production
- **`develop`** -- integration branch for the current sprint; merged to `main` at sprint end
- **Feature branches** -- `MED-xxx` format, branched from `develop`
- **Hotfix branches** -- `hotfix/MED-xxx`, branched from `main`, merged to both `main` and `develop`
- **Release branches** -- `release/vX.Y.Z`, cut from `develop` for final QA before merging to `main`

### Pull Request Guidelines

- **Base branch**: `develop` for features; `main` for hotfixes
- **PR title format**: `MED-{id}: {Story Title}`
- **Assignee**: Always assign to yourself (`--assignee @me`)
- **Reviewers**: Minimum 2 approvals required; 1 must be a senior engineer or tech lead
- **CI gates**: Lint, typecheck, full test suite, security scan (Bandit + safety), Docker build must all pass
- **Merge strategy**: Squash and merge for features; regular merge for release and hotfix branches
- **PR description**: Must include link to Linear ticket, summary of changes, and migration notes if applicable
- **HIPAA review**: Any PR touching `src/models/patient.py`, `src/services/fhir.py`, or `src/integrations/ehr/` requires compliance team review

## Integrations

- **CI/CD**: GitHub Actions (workflows in `.github/workflows/`)
  - `ci.yml` -- lint, typecheck, test, security scan on every push
  - `deploy-dev.yml` -- auto-deploy to dev on merge to `develop`
  - `deploy-staging.yml` -- deploy to staging on release branch push (auto after CI passes)
  - `deploy-prod.yml` -- deploy to production on merge to `main` (requires manual approval gate)
- **Infrastructure**: AWS
  - **Compute**: ECS Fargate (API) + ECS Fargate (Celery workers)
  - **Database**: RDS PostgreSQL 16 (Multi-AZ in prod)
  - **Cache/Broker**: ElastiCache Redis 7 cluster
  - **Storage**: S3 for clinical document uploads (encrypted at rest with KMS)
  - **Queue**: SQS for dead-letter queues and async event processing
  - **Secrets**: AWS Secrets Manager for API keys, DB credentials, JWT signing keys
- **Monitoring**: Datadog APM for traces + CloudWatch for logs + PagerDuty for on-call alerts
- **Error tracking**: Sentry (DSN in env vars; HIPAA BAA in place)
- **EHR Integration**: HL7 FHIR R4 adapters for Epic and Cerner (credentials in Secrets Manager)
- **Payments**: Stripe for patient billing (test mode in dev/staging, live in prod)
- **Notifications**: Twilio for SMS, SendGrid for email
- **Security scanning**: Bandit (static analysis), safety (dependency vulnerabilities), Snyk (container scanning)
